# 🌍 Types of APIs

# 1. Public APIs (Open APIs)

These APIs are available to external developers.

Companies expose them so others can build applications using their services.

📌 Example:

YouTube Data API

A developer can search videos without opening YouTube.

Request:

```text
Search: "Machine Learning"
```

Response:

```json
[
  {
    "title": "ML Tutorial",
    "views": 100000
  }
]
```

# 2. Private APIs (Internal APIs)

These APIs are only used inside a company.

Users never see them.

📌 Example:

Amazon Order Placement

When you place an order:

```text
Order API
     ↓
Inventory API
     ↓
Payment API
     ↓
Shipping API
```

Each API performs one responsibility.

This approach is common in microservices.

# 3. Library APIs

Not all APIs involve servers.

Programming languages also expose APIs.

📌 Example:

Python:

```python
numbers.sort()
```

You don't need to know how sorting works internally.

You simply call the API.

Similarly:

```python
list.append()
dict.get()
sorted()
```

are all APIs.

# 📡 API Communication Methods

Different APIs communicate differently.

# 1. REST API

REST is the most common API style.

It uses HTTP methods:

```text
GET
POST
PUT
DELETE
```

📌 Example:

Get all books:

```http
GET /books
```

Response:

```json
[
  {
    "id": 1,
    "title": "Clean Code"
  }
]
```

Why REST is popular:

* Simple
* Scalable
* Easy to understand
* Uses JSON

Most web applications today use REST.

# 2. SOAP API

SOAP is older and uses XML.

It is more strict and standardized.

📌 Common Uses:

* Banking
* Insurance
* Healthcare

Example:

```xml
<GetAccountBalance>
  <Account>12345</Account>
</GetAccountBalance>
```

SOAP is heavier than REST but provides stronger enterprise features.

# 3. GraphQL

GraphQL lets clients request exactly the data they need.

REST often returns too much or too little data.

GraphQL solves this.

📌 Example:

Request:

```graphql
{
  user(id: 123) {
    name
    email
  }
}
```

Response:

```json
{
  "name": "Alice",
  "email": "alice@example.com"
}
```

Only requested fields are returned.

This reduces network overhead.

# 4. gRPC

gRPC was developed by Google.

Instead of JSON, it uses Protocol Buffers (Protobuf).

Benefits:

* Smaller payloads
* Faster communication
* Supports streaming

📌 Common Uses:

* Microservices
* Internal service communication

Large companies often use:

```text
External APIs → REST
Internal APIs → gRPC
```

# 🔐 API Authentication

Most APIs don't allow anonymous access.

Authentication verifies who is making the request.

Common methods:

# API Keys

```text
api_key=abc123
```

Simple but limited.

# JWT Tokens

User logs in once.

Server generates token.

Client sends token with every request.

```text
Authorization: Bearer JWT_TOKEN
```

Very common in modern systems.

# OAuth

Used by:

* Google Login
* GitHub Login
* Facebook Login

Allows one service to access another securely.

